cos(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n### But wait, in the above two examples, the combination is the same except for one term. So, these two functions are not unique in their combination of allowed operations.\n\n### Therefore, the functions must have a unique combination of allowed operations.\n\n### So, each function must combine allowed operations in a way that no two functions have the same combination.\n\n### Each function must use a unique set of allowed operations.\n\n### So, for example:\n\nFunction 1 uses allowed operations 1, 8, 9, 10.\n\nFunction 2 uses allowed operations 2, 8, 9, 10.\n\nFunction 3 uses allowed operations 3, 8, 9, 10.\n\nAnd so on, ensuring each function uses a unique combination.\n\n### Now, proceed to generate 10 unique functions.\n\n### Now, I'll proceed to write each function with a unique combination of allowed operations.\n</think>\n\nTo solve the bin packing problem using heuristics, we need to generate 10 unique functions that compute a priority score for each bin. Each function must use a unique combination of allowed operations to ensure diversity in the heuristic approaches.\n\n### Approach\nThe approach involves creating 10 distinct functions, each using a unique combination of allowed operations. These operations include mathematical functions and aggregations that help determine how well each bin can accommodate the item. The goal is to minimize the loss, which is the sum of absolute differences between the item and each bin's capacity.\n\n### Solution Code\n```python\nimport numpy as np\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.mean(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.std(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.cos(np.pi * (item 