as into code without using loops, conditionals, or list comprehensions in the main function.\n\nLet's start with the first function:\n\nFunction 1:\nCompute the ratio of item to the remaining space of each bin. Higher ratio means higher priority.\n\nBut how to compute remaining space? Each bin's capacity is presumably 1 (as it's common in bin packing). So remaining space is 1 - bins[i].\n\nSo for each bin, remaining = 1 - bins[i]. Then priority is item / remaining.\n\nBut wait, if a bin is full, remaining is zero, which would cause division by zero. So perhaps add a small epsilon to avoid that.\n\nBut since the function must not have conditionals, maybe we can't handle that in the main function. So perhaps proceed, assuming bins have some space.\n\nSo:\n\npriority = item / (1 - bins)\n\nBut wait, the bins array could have values greater than 1? Or are they the current sum of items in the bin, which must be <=1.\n\nAssuming bins are the sum of items in each bin, each element is <=1.\n\nSo 1 - bins gives the remaining space.\n\nSo function 1:\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining = 1 - bins\n    return item / remaining\n\nBut in code, it's better to compute it inline.\n\nSo:\n\nreturn item / (1 - bins)\n\nBut wait, what if bins has a 1 in it? Then division by zero. So perhaps add a small epsilon, like 1e-8.\n\nBut since the function can't have conditionals, perhaps we can't do that. So maybe proceed without handling it, but in practice, the bin packing algorithm would avoid full bins.\n\nBut for the function, we have to return an array. So proceed.\n\nFunction 1 code:\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return item / (1 - bins)\n\nBut wait, 1 - bins may be negative if bins has a value >1, but in bin packing, bins can't have more than 1, so perhaps it's safe.\n\nFunction 2:\n\nUse the difference between the bin's current load and the item. So for each bin, priority is (1 - bins[i]) - item. But wait, that would prioritize bins where the remaining space is larger than the item.\n\nAlternatively, priority could be (1 - bins[i]) / item.\n\nWait, let's think differently. Maybe use the ratio of the remaining space to the item size. So for each bin, priority is (1 - bins[i]) / item.\n\nBut that would prioritize bins with more remaining space relative to the item.\n\nSo function 2:\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (1 - bins) / item\n\nBut wait, if item is zero, division by zero. But item is a float, presumably positive. But in practice, item can't be zero in bin packing.\n\nBut the function must handle all cases, so perhaps proceed.\n\nFunction 3:\n\nUse the sum of the bin's current load and the item. So priority is bins[i] + item. But that would prioritize bins that are already heavy. Maybe not useful.\n\nAlternatively, use the product: bins * item.\n\nBut that would prioritize bins that have higher current load and higher item. Not sure.\n\nAlternatively, use the difference: 1 - (bins + item). But that's similar to function 1.\n\nWait, perhaps function 3 can be:\n\nUse the bin's current load multiplied by the item. So priority is bins * item.\n\nBut that would prioritize bins that are already full, which might not be good.\n\nAlternatively, use the bin's remaining space multiplied by the item: (1 - bins) * item.\n\nBut that's similar to function 1.\n\nAlternatively, use the bin's current load plus the item, divided by something.\n\nWait, maybe use the bin's current load plus the item, but that's not necessarily a good metric.\n\nAlternatively, use the bin's current load divided by the item.\n\nBut perhaps function 3 can be:\n\npriority = (1 - bins) - item\n\nSo the priority is the remaining space minus the item size. So bins with more remaining space and smaller items get higher priority.\n\nBut how does that work? For example, if a bin has 0.5 remaining, and item is 0.3, then 0.5 -0.3=0.2. If another bin has 0.4 remaining, 0.4-0.3=0.1. So the first bin is better.\n\nBut if the item is 0.6, then 0.5-0.6=-0.1, which is worse than 0.4-0.6=-0.2. So the second bin is better, which makes sense because 0.4 is closer to 0.6.\n\nWait, but in bin packing, you want to place the item in a bin where it fits. So perhaps the priority should be based on how much space is left after placing the item.\n\nSo perhaps the priority is (1 - bins[i] - item). But that would be negative if the item doesn't fit.\n\nWait, but the function must return a priority score, which is a number that the algorithm uses to choose the next bin. So perhaps the priority is higher for bins that can fit the item and have more space.\n\nSo, for bins where bins[i] + item <=1, the priority could be (1 - bins[i] - item). For bins where it's not possible, the priority is zero or negative.\n\nBut the function needs to compute this for all bins.\n\nBut how to compute it without conditionals.\n\nWait, perhaps the priority is (1 - bins[i] - item) for bins where bins[i] + item <=1, else 0.\n\nBut in code, how to do that without conditionals.\n\nAlternatively, compute (1 - bins[i] - item), and for bins where this is negative, set to zero.\n\nBut without conditionals, perhaps use the max function.\n\nSo priority = np.maximum(0, 1 - bins - item)\n\nBut in the main function, can we use np.maximum?\n\nYes, as it's an allowed operation.\n\nSo function 3:\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.maximum(0, 1 - bins - item)\n\nThis way, bins where the item can fit (1 - bins >= item) will have positive priority, and others will have zero.\n\nBut wait, the item is a float, and bins are an array. So 1 - bins is an array, subtracting item (a scalar) gives an array. So yes.\n\nFunction 4:\n\nUse the bin's current load squared plus the item. So priority = bins**2 + item.\n\nBut not sure if that's useful.\n\nAlternatively, use the bin's current load multiplied by the item: bins * item.\n\nBut perhaps function 4 can be: