e of remaining space\n- The square root of remaining space\n- The mean or standard deviation of bins\n- The mean or standard deviation of remaining space\n- Any combination of the above operations\n\nEach implementation must use a unique combination of these operations to compute the priority.\n\n### Task Breakdown:\n1. For each of the 10 implementations, choose a different combination of mathematical functions, array operations, and heuristics to compute the priority.\n\n2. Ensure that the function returns an array of the same shape as bins.\n\n3. Ensure that all operations are vectorized and do not involve any loops or conditionals that require loops.\n\n4. Each implementation must be correct, meaning that higher priority scores should correspond to more suitable bins for the item.\n\n### Final Deliverable:\nSubmit 10 unique implementations of the priority function, each using a different combination of allowed operations.\n\n### Final Note:\nThe priority function will be used in a bin packing algorithm, so the higher the priority score, the higher the chance the item is placed in that bin.\n\n### Example of How to Write Each Implementation:\n\nFor each implementation, write a function as per the signature, and then provide the loss value, which is the loss computed when the function is used in the bin packing algorithm. The loss is computed as the total wasted space across all bins after packing.\n\n### Final Instructions:\nSubmit 10 unique implementations, each with a unique combination of allowed operations, and provide the loss value for each.\n\n---\n\n### Task: Generate 10 Unique Implementations of the priority function.\n\n### Allowed Operations:\n- Mathematical functions: abs, exp, sin, cos, sqrt, log, log10, pi, e\n- Array operations: mean, std, exp, sin, cos, log, log10, abs, mod, add, subtract, multiply, divide, floor, ceil, round\n- Logical operations: any, all, where, select, invert, logical_and, logical_or, logical_xor, logical_not, max, min\n- Other operations: np.newaxis, append, insert, delete, sort, argsort, bincount, unique, cumsum, cumprod, diff, gradient\n- List/array manipulations: same as above\n- Indexing/slicing: various\n- Conditional functions: where, select, max, min, any, all\n- Constants: pi, e, inf, nan, rint, floor, ceil\n\nEach implementation must use a unique combination of these operations, ensuring that each function is different from the others.\n\n### Hints:\n- Use different mathematical functions in combination.\n- Apply different transformations to the bins and item.\n- Combine multiple factors into the priority score.\n- Use different array operations to compute the priority.\n\n### Example Implementations:\n\nHere are some examples of how you can create unique implementations:\n\n1. **Implementation 1**:\n   def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n       remaining = bins - item\n       remaining[remaining < 0] = -np.inf\n       priority = np.abs(remaining - item)\n       return priority\n\n   This implementation uses subtraction to find remaining space, sets invalid bins to -inf, and calculates priority based on the difference between remaining space and item size.\n\n2. **Implementation 2**:\n   def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n       remaining = bins - item\n       priority = np.exp(remaining) / (item + 1)\n       return priority\n\n   Here, the priority is calculated using the exponential of remaining space divided by (item + 1).\n\n3. **Implementation 3**:\n   def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n       remaining = bins - item\n       priority = np.sin(np.pi * remaining / item)\n       return priority\n\n   This implementation uses the sine function with a ratio of remaining space to item size.\n\n4. **Implementation 4**:\n   def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n       remaining = bins - item\n       priority = np.sqrt(remaining) / (item + 1)\n       return priority\n\n   Priority is the 