y) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.sqrt(item) * np.mean(bins) + np.log(np.max(bins) / item)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.tanh(item / bins) + np.mean(bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.where(bins >= item, np.exp(-(bins - item)/bins), -np.inf)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + bins) / (item - bins + 1e-8) + np.log(bins + 1e-8)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.sin(bins) * np.cos(item) + np.log(bins + 1e-8)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    # Compute how much space is left in each bin\n    remaining = bins - item\n    # Only consider bins that can fit the item\n    can_fit = remaining >= 0\n    # For bins that can\'t fit, set their priority to -infinity\n    remaining[~can_fit] = -np.inf\n    # Find the bin with the largest remaining space (worst fit)\n    return remaining\n\nThis function uses the "Worst Fit" heuristic, where it tries to place the item in the bin with the largest remaining space.\n\n### Example of Another Heuristic:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    # Compute how much space is left in each bin\n    remaining = bins - item\n    # For bins that can\'t fit the item, set priority to -infinity\n    remaining[remaining < 0] = -np.inf\n    # Find the bin with the smallest remaining space (best fit)\n    return remaining\n\nThis function uses the "Best Fit" heuristic, which tries to minimize the residual space.\n\n### Another Example:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    # Compute how much space is left in each bin\n    remaining = bins - item\n    # For bins that can\'t fit the item, set priority to -infinity\n    remaining[remaining < 0] = -np.inf\n    # Find the bin with the largest remaining space (worst fit)\n    # Multiply by a factor that penalizes larger remaining space\n    return remaining * (1 + 1/remaining)\n\nThis function penalizes bins with larger remaining space more, encouraging better fit.\n\n### Another Example:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    # Compute how much space is left in each bin\n    remaining = bins - item\n    # For bins that can\'t fit the item, set priority to -infinity\n    remaining[remaining < 0] = -np.inf\n    # Compute the ratio of remaining space to bin capacity\n    ratio = remaining / bins\n    # Prioritize bins with higher remaining ratios (worst fit)\n    return ratio\n\nThis function uses the ratio of remaining space to bin capacity as the priority.\n\n### Another Example:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    # Compute how much space is left in each bin\n    remaining = bins - item\n    # For bins that can\'t fit the item, set priority to -infinity\n    remaining[remaining < 0] = -np.inf\n    # Compute the difference between remaining space and item size\n    diff = remaining - item\n    # Prioritize bins where the difference is minimized (best fit)\n    return diff\n\nThis function uses the difference between remaining space and item size, trying to minimize the residual space.\n\n### Another Example:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    # Compute how much space is left in each bin\n    remaining = bins - item\n    # For bins that can\'t fit the item, set priority to -infinity\n    remaining[remaining < 0] = -np.inf\n    # Compute the sum of remaining space and item size\n    sum_space = remaining + item\n    # Prioritize bins with smaller sum of remaining and item (best fit)\n    return sum_space\n\nThis function prioritizes bins where the sum of remaining space and item size is minimized.\n\n### Another Example:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    # Compute how much space is left in each bin\n    remaining = bins - item\n    # For bins that can\'t fit the item, set priority to -infinity\n    remaining[remaining < 0] = -np.inf\n    # Compute the product of remaining space and item size\n    product = remaining * item\n    # Prioritize bins with higher product (best fit)\n    return product\n\nThis function prioritizes bins where the product of remaining space and item size is higher.\n\n### Another Example:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    # Compute how much space is left in each bin\n    remaining = bins - item\n    # For bins that can\'t fit the item, set priority to -infinity\n    remaining[remaining < 0] = -np.inf\n    # Compute the difference between remaining space and item size\n    diff = remaining - item\n    # Prioritize bins where the difference is minimized (best fit)\n    return diff\n\nThis function is similar to an earlier example but uses a different calculation.\n\n### Another Example:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    # Compute how much space is left in each bin\n    remaining = bins - item\n    # For bins that can\'t fit the item, set priority to -infinity\n    remaining[remaining < 0] = -np.inf\n    # Compute the ratio of remaining space to item size\n    ratio = remaining / item\n    # Prioritize bins with higher ratio (best fit)\n    return ratio\n\nThis function uses the ratio of remaining space to item size as the priority.\n\n### Another Example:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    # Compute how much space is left in each bin\n    remaining = bins - item\n    # For bins that can\'t fit the item, set priority to -infinity\n    remaining[remaining < 0] = -np.inf\n    # Compute the reciprocal of remaining space\n    reciprocal = 1 / remaining\n    # Prioritize bins with smaller reciprocal (best fit)\n    return reciprocal\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.sqrt(item) * np.exp(np.mean(bins)) + np.tan(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.log(item + np.min(bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bi